# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 49th-parallel-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The **2017 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2017 or IC17) was the sixth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, a triennial international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 5–19 August 2017, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous men's tournament champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Previous women's winners (Ireland and Canada) also competed in the tournament.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea achieved its 3rd men's title and Ireland achieved its 2nd women's title.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The 2017 AFL International Cup was played in Melbourne from 5 to 19 August, with 18 men's teams and eight women's teams competing.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The European Crusaders was a combined team made up of women from Britain, Croatia, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Poland and Sweden.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] In the table below, the numbers in parentheses refer to the team's Unofficial World Rankings by *World Footy News* prior to the competition.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] For the first time, the men's fixture was played across two divisions.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Division One played four matches against other teams within the division and were ranked from one to ten, with finals to follow between the top two placed teams on the ladder, the third and fourth placed teams, and so on.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's Division Two competition and the women's competition saw teams split into two pools of four with each team playing matches against the three opponents in their pool before competing in semi-finals and grand finals based on finishing positions within the pool.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The women's grand final was played at Etihad Stadium as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 clash between Carlton and Hawthorn.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's grand final was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 match between Collingwood and Geelong.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The majority of the matches were played at Royal Park in the Melbourne suburb of Parkville.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The inclusion of a "Community Round" allowed matches to be played as curtain-raisers to local suburban, amateur and country matches.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally, the International Cup introduced a "School Round" to be played on 9 August, with games played at suburban and country schools.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Fixtures for the tournament were released by the AFL on 18 July 2017.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The **49th Parallel Cup** (formerly PanAm Cup) is an annual representative Australian rules football match between the United States and Canada first contested in 1999.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/49th-parallel-cup] Since 2007 the women's teams have also contested the cup.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The men's matches are contested between the United States men's team ("The Revolution") and Canada's men's team ("The Northwind") while the women's matches are contested between the United States women's team ("The Freedom") and Canada's women's team ("The Northern Lights").
[src:49th-parallel-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The cup is historically paused during the Australian Football International Cup year to enable the countries to compete at that tournament.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/49th-parallel-cup] Between 2015 and 2021 the cup went into recess for several reasons, primarily due to the 2017 Australian Football International Cup followed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] AFL Canada was formed on 30 July 2004, when the Canadian Australian Football Association changed its official name.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] AFL Canada is responsible for co-ordinating three national programs - the Northwind senior men, Northern Lights senior women and the Wolfpack junior men's team.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] AFL Canada also oversees game development nationally and several competitions and tournaments across the country.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] The Canadian Australian Football Association was established in May 1989 when two clubs, the Mississauga Mustangs (now the High Park Demons) and the Toronto Panthers (now the Toronto Eagles), were formed and played in the inaugural Conacher Cup game in Toronto, Ontario.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] AFL Canada selects the Northwind, Canada's national men's Australian rules football team, and the Northern Lights, Canada's national women's team.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] Northwind and Northern Lights players are selected from the best Canadian-born players from the clubs across the country, with both teams playing in international tournaments and exhibition matches.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] The Northwind have competed at every edition of the triennial Australian Football International Cup, at which they have finished as high as fifth.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] The Northern Lights have competed at all three editions of the women's tournament, making every final of the International Cup and winning the tournament in 2014.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] Both national teams also compete against the United States at the 49th Parallel Cup, with the Northern Lights undefeated since 2012.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] AFL Canada has also put forward the Wolfpack, a junior men's team, which has played games in Australia.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] The Northwind have competed at the Australian Football International Cup since their first appearance in 2002.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] The International Cup is a competition where players that are citizens of the countries who are competing are the only players allowed to play (no expatriate Australians are permitted to play, with teams composed solely of amateurs who must be nationals of the country they represent).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-canada] In the 2002 Australian Football International Cup the Canada Northwind finished 9th of 11 teams.
