[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] AFL Ontario, along with the North West Pacific Football League is a member of AFL Canada, the governing body for the sport in Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] AFL Ontario which was originally known as the Canadian Australian Football League (CAFA) and more recently as the Ontario Australian Football League (OAFL), was established in 1989.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] Two teams were formed that year - the Toronto Panthers and the Mississauga Mustangs, with a draft of interested players prior to a three-game season and Grand Final.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] The coaches of those inaugural teams – John Pearson (Toronto Panthers) and Terence Wallis (Mississauga Mustangs) brought a significant amount of experience from playing at a high level in Australia.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] An interesting fact is that the first Grand Final was attended by a number of AFL executives including Ron Barrassi and members of the Geelong Cats and Melbourne Demons.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] These pioneers set the foundation for the current competition.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] During the early years CAFA played a number of International games against visiting teams from Australia (Balmain FC, Golden Oldies touring team) as well as the team representing the Australian Rules league in England.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] The Canadian team narrowly missed beating the touring Australian teams over the years, but soundly defeated England on the four occasions that it played them (1990–1996) culminating in a strong win by the touring Canadian team in London (1996) coached by Terence Wallis.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] In 2011, with the increased interest in women's football, AFL Ontario established their Women's League with great success.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] With the help of the Ontario Trillium Foundation, 2011 also saw the development of AFL Ontario's junior competition.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] 2012 saw the women's division double in size to 6 teams competing, and the junior competition continued over the summer holidays.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] In 2009, AFL Ontario launched a second division originally consisting of six founding teams.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] London (Ontario) AFC withdrew before the official start to the season and the team's players were absorbed into the Quebec Saints.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] Along with the Saints, the Toronto Central Blues, Broadview Hawks, Etobicoke 'Old Boys' Roos and Toronto Eagles made up the founding five teams of the new OAFL Division 2 competition.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] In honour of the first Canadian to ever play in the AFL the competition's premiership cup was named the **Mike Pyke Cup** (named after Mike Pyke).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] The OAFL Division 2 season was traditionally shorter than that of the OAFL.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] In 2009 due to teams playing different numbers of matches the ladder was determined by 'Match Ratio' rather than premiership points.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] In 2010 all teams competed in 8 rounds and thus the ladder reverted to determining positions by premiership points.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] 2010 also saw the introduction of hybrid teams.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] New team the Toronto Rebel Dogs (a partnership between the Toronto Downtown Dingos and the Toronto Rebels) and the 'DevilRoos' (a partnership between the Etobicoke Roos and High Park Demons).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] The Toronto Eagles withdrew their team from the 2010 season.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] Location map of current clubs in the league.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] In 2006, AFL Ontario had around 330 senior players consisting of over 170 Canadian nationals.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-ontario] With the rapid increase in awareness and interest in Australian football in Ontario, this has increased in 2012 with almost 650 senior men and women members.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The creation of the Québec Saints in early 2008 and their participation in the Toronto-based 'Rec' Footy league that same year led to a growing interest in Australian Football in Montréal.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] To capitalise on the popularity, club founder Luke Anderson launched a locally based 9-a-side competition named the Eastern Canadian Australian Football League or ECAFL.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The 9-a-side format of the game is played on reduced size fields (usually rugby or soccer fields).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] Players from the Québec Saints were drafted into two subsidiary teams, the first match of the newly formed league was played on 4 October 2008 between the Montréal Saints and Laval Bombers at Parc Cartier in Laval.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] 2009 saw the league schedule seven regular season games and one final and launch the introduction of an invitational Pre-Season tournament.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The league also introduced women's football for the first time.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The newly formed Montréal Angels (a branch of the Québec Saints), played exhibition games against the Toronto Central Blues and Montréal Shamrocks Gaelic Football team.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] Players from the 9-a-side competition where eligible to play representative football for the Québec Saints who were competing in the Ontario AFL Division 2.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] With increasing player numbers, the 2010 season saw the launch of a third Montréal based team, the Pointe Claire Power.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The invitational pre-season cup was contested by a record six teams and for the first time included a women's division.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The league established a home field at Parc Cluny in Laval.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The season was reduced to five rounds to accommodate the Québec Saints Ontario AFL schedule, the representative 18-a-side team's fixture featuring a marked increase in games in Ottawa and Toronto.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] Club and league founder Luke Anderson departed Montréal in late 2010 and the newly formed committee under the leadership of new president Renaud Carbonell made several changes to the league's structure.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] Major changes included the Québec Saints withdrawing from the Ontario AFL's Division 2 competition and AFL Québec returning to the original two teams with the folding of the 2010 premiers the Pointe Claire Power.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] While player participation experienced a drop-off in 2011, Montréal still had a significant football presence with a host of players and coaches participating in 'IC11', the International Cup of Australian Football co-hosted by Melbourne and Sydney, Australia.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] 2012 saw a resurgence of Australian Football.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The league was rebranded 'AFL Quebec' and expanded to four teams (The Laval Bombers, Melbourne Demons, Fremantle Dockers and West Coast Eagles) - three of which had official backing from AFL teams, thanks to the initiative of William T. - and Montreal would be represented at the U.S.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] Nationals football tournament for the first time, albeit as a combine team.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] The growing interest in Aussie Rules would continue for the next few years before the league officially announced the creation of a women's division for 2014 with the creation of the N.D.G.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/afl-quebec] In 2015 the women's league expanded to four teams when Ottawa entered the Carleton Warriors and the Rideau Shamrocks into the competition.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] The **Alberta Footy Women's League (AFWL)** is the largest women's Australian football league playing regular matches in North America.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] It is currently composed of teams from Calgary and Edmonton, Alberta, who play for the AFWL Premiership Cup.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] The AFWL, along with the Ontario Australian Football League and North West Pacific Football League is a member of AFL Canada, the governing body for the sport in Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] In 2008, the AFWL had around 90 senior players consisting of over 70 Canadian nationals.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] The league grew out of intra-club matches organized by the Calgary Kookaburras in 2007.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] A move was made the next season to formalize the league, and Calgary's players were drafted into two clubs based in inner-suburban Calgary - Hillhurst and Kensington.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] The 2008 season ran from May to September and consisted of 12 rounds of matches.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] Hillhurst won the inaugural Premiership when they defeated Kensington 5.0.30 to 1.7.13 at Queen Elizabeth School on September 28, 2008.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] The Edmonton Emus were founded in 2009 to become the AFWL's third team and bring women's footy to central Alberta for the first time.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] The 2009 season ran from May to September, featuring five rounds of double-header matches and a finals series.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-footy-women-s-league] Hillhurst defeated Edmonton 12.9.81 to 0.0.0 in the Preliminary Final and went on to defeat Kensington in the Grand Final - 5.7.37 to 1.7.13 - at McNally High School (Edmonton) on September 19, 2009.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta's economy is advanced, open, market-based, and characterized by a highly educated workforce, strong institutions and property rights, and sophisticated financial markets.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The service sector employs 80% of Albertans, in fields like healthcare, education, professional services, retail, tourism and financial services.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The industrial base includes manufacturing, construction, and agriculture (10%, 5%, and 2% of employment respectively), while the knowledge economy includes about 3000 tech companies employing an estimated 60,000 people, mainly in Calgary and Edmonton.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The energy sector employs 5% of Albertans but significantly impacts exports and GDP.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta's exports, primarily US-bound, consist of 70% oil and gas, 13% food products, and 12% industrial products.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Oil and gas are culturally influential, having shaped politics, generated "striking it rich" narratives, and created boom-and-bust cycles.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 2023, Alberta's output was $350 billion, 15% of Canada's GDP.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Until the 1930s, Alberta's political landscape consisted of two major parties: the centre-left Liberals and the agrarian United Farmers of Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Today, Alberta is generally perceived as a conservative province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The right-wing Social Credit Party held office continually from 1935 to 1971 before the centre-right Progressive Conservatives held office continually from 1971 to 2015, the latter being the longest unbroken run in government at the provincial or federal level in Canadian history.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The United Conservative Party has held office since 2019.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Since before it became part of Canada, Alberta has been home to several First Nations, such as Plains Indians and Woodland Cree.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] It was historically also a territory used by fur traders of the rival companies Hudson's Bay Company and North West Company.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Dominion of Canada bought the lands that would become Alberta as part of the NWT in 1870.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] From the late 1800s to the early 1900s, many immigrants arrived in an effort to prevent the prairies from being annexed by the United States.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Growing wheat and cattle ranching became very profitable during this period.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 1905, the Alberta Act was passed, creating the province of Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Massive oil reserves were discovered in 1947.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The exploitation of oil sands began in 1967.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta is renowned for its natural beauty and is home to important nature reserves.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] It is also well known as a rich source of fossils.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] It is home to six UNESCO-designated World Heritage Sites: the Canadian Rocky Mountain Parks, Dinosaur Provincial Park, Head-Smashed-In Buffalo Jump, Waterton-Glacier International Peace Park, Wood Buffalo National Park and Writing-on-Stone Provincial Park.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Other popular sites include Banff National Park, Elk Island National Park, Jasper National Park, Waterton Lakes National Park, and Drumheller.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta was named after Princess Louise Caroline Alberta (1848–1939), the fourth daughter of Queen Victoria.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Princess Louise was the wife of John Campbell, Marquess of Lorne, Governor General of Canada (1878–83).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Lake Louise and Mount Alberta were also named in her honour.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The name "Alberta" is a feminine Latinized form of Albert, the name of Princess Louise's father, the Prince Consort (cf.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Medieval Latin: *Albertus*, masculine) and its Germanic cognates, ultimately derived from the Proto-Germanic language **Aþalaberhtaz* (compound of "noble" + "bright/famous").
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta, with an area of 661,848 km2 (255,541 sq mi), is the fourth-largest province after Quebec, Ontario, and British Columbia.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta's southern border is the 49th parallel north, which separates it from the U.S. state of Montana.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The 60th parallel north divides Alberta from the Northwest Territories.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The province extends 1,223 kilometres (760 mi) north to south and 660 km (410 mi) east to west at its maximum width.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Its highest point is 3,747 metres (12,293 ft) at the summit of Mount Columbia in the Rocky Mountains along the southwest border while its lowest point is 152 m (499 ft) on the Slave River in Wood Buffalo National Park in the northeast.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] With the exception of the semi-arid climate of the steppe in the south-eastern section, the province has adequate water resources.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] There are numerous rivers and lakes in Alberta used for swimming, fishing and a range of water sports.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] There are three large lakes, Lake Claire (1,436 km2 [554 sq mi]) in Wood Buffalo National Park, Lesser Slave Lake (1,168 km2 or 451 sq mi), and Lake Athabasca (7,898 km2 or 3,049 sq mi), which lies in both Alberta and Saskatchewan.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The longest river in the province is the Athabasca River, which travels 1,538 km (956 mi) from the Columbia Icefield in the Rocky Mountains to Lake Athabasca.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The largest river is the Peace River with an average flow of 2,100 cubic metres per second (74,000 cu ft/s).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Peace River originates in the Rocky Mountains of northern British Columbia and flows through northern Alberta and into the Slave River, a tributary of the Mackenzie River.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta's capital city, Edmonton, is located roughly at the geographic centre of the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] It is the most northerly major city in Canada and serves as a gateway and hub for resource development in northern Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] With its proximity to Canada's largest oil fields, the region has most of western Canada's oil refinery capacity.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Calgary is about 280 km (170 mi) south of Edmonton and 240 km (150 mi) north of Montana by highway, surrounded by extensive ranching country.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Almost 75% of the province's population lives in the Calgary–Edmonton Corridor.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The land grant policy to the railways served as a means to populate the province in its early years.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Most of the northern half of the province is boreal forest, while the Rocky Mountains along the southwestern boundary are largely temperate coniferous forests of the Alberta Mountain forests and Alberta–British Columbia foothills forests.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The southern quarter of the province is prairie, ranging from shortgrass prairie in the southeastern corner to mixed grass prairie in an arc to the west and north of it.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The central aspen parkland region extending in a broad arc between the prairies and the forests, from Calgary, north to Edmonton, and then east to Lloydminster, contains the most fertile soil in the province and most of the population.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Much of the unforested part of Alberta is given over either to grain farming or cattle ranching, with mixed farming more common in the north and centre, while ranching and irrigated agriculture predominate in the south.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Alberta badlands are in southeastern Alberta, where the Red Deer River crosses the flat prairie and farmland, and features deep canyons and striking landforms.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Dinosaur Provincial Park, near Brooks, showcases the badlands terrain, desert flora, and remnants from Alberta's past when dinosaurs roamed the then lush landscape.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta extends for over 1,200 km (750 mi) from north to south; its climate, therefore, varies considerably.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Average high temperatures in January range from 0 °C (32 °F) in the southwest to −24 °C (−11 °F) in the far north.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The northerly location and isolation from the weather systems of the Pacific Ocean cause Alberta to have a dry climate with little moderation from the ocean.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Annual precipitation ranges from 300 millimetres (12 in) in the southeast to 450 mm (18 in) in the north, except in the foothills of the Rocky Mountains where total precipitation including snowfall can reach 600 mm (24 in) annually.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Northern Alberta is mostly covered by boreal forest and has a subarctic climate.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The agricultural area of southern Alberta has a semi-arid steppe climate because the annual precipitation is less than the water that evaporates or is used by plants.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The southeastern corner of Alberta, part of the Palliser Triangle, experiences greater summer heat and lower rainfall than the rest of the province, and as a result, suffers frequent crop yield problems and occasional severe droughts.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Western Alberta is protected by the mountains and enjoys the mild temperatures brought by winter Chinook winds.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Central and parts of northwestern Alberta in the Peace River region are largely aspen parkland, a biome transitional between prairie to the south and boreal forest to the north.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta has a humid continental climate with warm summers and cold winters.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The province is open to cold Arctic weather systems from the north, which often produce cold winter conditions.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] As the fronts between the air masses shift north and south across Alberta, the temperature can change rapidly.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Arctic air masses in the winter produce extreme minimum temperatures varying from −54 °C (−65 °F) in northern Alberta to −46 °C (−51 °F) in southern Alberta, although temperatures at these extremes are rare.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In the summer, continental air masses have produced record maximum temperatures from 32 °C (90 °F) in the mountains to over 40 °C (104 °F) in southeastern Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Annual bright sunshine totals range between 1,900 up to just under 2,600 hours per year.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Northern Alberta gets about 18 hours of daylight in the summer.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The average daytime temperatures range from around 21 °C (70 °F) in the Rocky Mountain valleys and far north, up to around 28 °C (82 °F) in the dry prairie of the southeast.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The northern and western parts of the province experience higher rainfall and lower evaporation rates caused by cooler summer temperatures.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The south and east-central portions are prone to drought-like conditions sometimes persisting for several years, although even these areas can receive heavy precipitation, sometimes resulting in flooding.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In the winter, the Alberta clipper, a type of intense, fast-moving winter storm that generally forms over or near the province and, pushed with great speed by the continental polar jetstream, descends over the rest of southern Canada and the northern tier of the United States.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In southwestern Alberta, the cold winters are frequently interrupted by warm, dry Chinook winds blowing from the mountains, which can propel temperatures upward from frigid conditions to well above the freezing point in a very short period.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] During one Chinook recorded at Pincher Creek, temperatures soared from −19 to 22 °C (−2 to 72 °F) in just one hour.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The region around Lethbridge has the most Chinooks, averaging 30 to 35 Chinook days per year.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Calgary has a 56% chance of a white Christmas, while Edmonton has an 86% chance.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] After Saskatchewan, Alberta experiences the most tornadoes in Canada with an average of 15 verified per year.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Thunderstorms, some of them severe, are frequent in the summer, especially in central and southern Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The region surrounding the Calgary–Edmonton Corridor is notable for having the highest frequency of hail in Canada, which is caused by orographic lifting from the nearby Rocky Mountains, enhancing the updraft/downdraft cycle necessary for the formation of hail.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In central and northern Alberta the arrival of spring is marked by the early flowering of the prairie crocus (*Pulsatilla nuttalliana*) *anemone*; this member of the buttercup family has been recorded flowering as early as March, though April is the usual month for the general population.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Other prairie flora known to flower early are the golden bean (*Thermopsis rhombifolia*) and wild rose (*Rosa acicularis*).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Members of the sunflower (*Helianthus*) family blossom on the prairie in the summer months between July and September.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The southern and east central parts of Alberta are covered by short prairie grass, which dries up as summer lengthens, to be replaced by hardy perennials such as the prairie coneflower (*Ratibida*), fleabane, and sage (*Artemisia*).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Both yellow and white sweet clover (*Melilotus*) can be found throughout the southern and central areas of the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The trees in the parkland region of the province grow in clumps and belts on the hillsides.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] These are largely deciduous, typically aspen, poplar, and willow.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Many species of willow and other shrubs grow in virtually any terrain.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] North of the North Saskatchewan River, evergreen forests prevail for thousands of square kilometres.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Aspen poplar, balsam poplar (*Populus balsamifera*) or in some parts cottonwood (*Populus deltoides*), and paper birch (*Betula papyrifera*) are the primary large deciduous species.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Conifers include jack pine (*Pinus banksiana*), Rocky Mountain pine, lodgepole pine (*Pinus contorta*), both white and black spruce, and the deciduous conifer tamarack (*Larix laricina*).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The four climatic regions (alpine, boreal forest, parkland, and prairie) of Alberta are home to many different species of animals.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The south and central prairie was the homeland of the American bison, also known as buffalo, with its grasses providing pasture and breeding ground for millions of buffalo.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The buffalo population was decimated during early settlement, but since then, buffalo have made a comeback, living on farms and in parks all over Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Herbivores are found throughout the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Moose, mule deer, elk, and white-tailed deer are found in the wooded regions, and pronghorn can be found in the prairies of southern Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Bighorn sheep and mountain goats live in the Rocky Mountains.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Rabbits, porcupines, skunks, squirrels, and many species of rodents and reptiles live in every corner of the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta is home to only one venomous snake species, the prairie rattlesnake.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta is home to many large carnivores such as wolves, grizzly bears, black bears, and mountain lions, which are found in the mountains and wooded regions.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Smaller carnivores of the canine and feline families include coyotes, red foxes, Canada lynx, and bobcats.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Wolverines can also be found in the northwestern areas of the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Central and northern Alberta and the region farther north are the nesting ground of many migratory birds.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Vast numbers of ducks, geese, swans and pelicans arrive in Alberta every spring and nest on or near one of the hundreds of small lakes that dot northern Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Eagles, hawks, owls, and crows are plentiful, and a huge variety of smaller seed and insect-eating birds can be found.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta, like other temperate regions, is home to mosquitoes, flies, wasps, and bees.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Rivers and lakes are populated with pike, walleye, whitefish, rainbow, speckled, brown trout, and sturgeon.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Native to the province, the bull trout, is the provincial fish and an official symbol of Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Turtles are found in some water bodies in the southern part of the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Frogs and salamanders are a few of the amphibians that make their homes in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta is the only province in Canada—as well as one of the few places in the world—that is free from Norwegian rats.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Since the early 1950s, the Government of Alberta has operated a rat-control program, which has been so successful that only isolated instances of wild rat sightings are reported, usually of rats arriving in the province aboard trucks or by rail.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 2006, Alberta Agriculture reported zero findings of wild rats; the only rat interceptions have been domesticated rats that have been seized from their owners.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] It is illegal for individual Albertans to own or keep Norwegian rats of any description; the animals can only be kept in the province by zoos, universities and colleges, and recognized research institutions.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 2009, several rats were found and captured, in small pockets in southern Alberta, putting Alberta's rat-free status in jeopardy.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] A colony of rats was subsequently found in a landfill near Medicine Hat in 2012 and again in 2014.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta has one of the greatest diversities and abundances of Late Cretaceous dinosaur fossils worldwide.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Taxa are represented by complete fossil skeletons, isolated material, microvertebrate remains, and even mass graves.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] At least 38 dinosaur type specimens were collected in the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Foremost Formation, Oldman Formation and Dinosaur Park Formations collectively compose the Judith River Group and are the most thoroughly studied dinosaur-bearing strata in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Dinosaur-bearing strata are distributed widely throughout Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Dinosaur Provincial Park area contains outcrops of the Dinosaur Park Formation and Oldman Formation.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In Alberta's central and southern regions are intermittent Scollard Formation outcrops.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In the Drumheller Valley and Edmonton regions there are exposed Horseshoe Canyon facies.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Other formations have been recorded as well, like the Milk River and Foremost Formations.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The latter two have a lower diversity of documented dinosaurs, primarily due to their lower total fossil quantity and neglect from collectors who are hindered by the isolation and scarcity of exposed outcrops.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Their dinosaur fossils are primarily teeth recovered from microvertebrate fossil sites.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Additional geologic formations that have produced only a few fossils are the Belly River Group and St.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Mary River Formations of the southwest and the northwestern Wapiti Formation, which contains two *Pachyrhinosaurus* bone beds.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Bearpaw Formation represents strata deposited during a marine transgression.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Dinosaurs are known from this formation, but represent specimens washed out to sea or reworked from older sediments.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Paleo-Indians arrived in what is now Alberta at least 10,000 years ago, toward the end of the last ice age.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] They are thought to have migrated from Siberia to Alaska on a land bridge across the Bering Strait and then possibly moved south along the east side of the Rocky Mountains through Alberta, settling along the way or moving on to settle other parts of the Americas.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Others may have travelled south along the west coast and then moved inland.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The first Europeans to visit Alberta were French Canadian fur traders in the early 18th century.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The first British subject to visit Alberta was Anthony Henday, in 1754.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] French Canadians integrated with local First Nations creating the Metis nation, with elements across the Prairies.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] French was the predominant European language in Alberta and was used in some early fur trading forts in the region, such as the first Fort Edmonton (in present-day Fort Saskatchewan), operated by the Hudson's Bay Company (HBC).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] After the British arrival in Canada, approximately half of Alberta's current territory, south of the Athabasca River drainage, became part of Rupert's Land, which consisted of all land drained by rivers flowing into Hudson Bay.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] This area was granted by King Charles II of England to the Hudson's Bay Company in 1670, and rival fur trading companies were not allowed to trade in it.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Athabasca River and the rivers north of it were not in HBC territory, because they drained into the Arctic Ocean instead of Hudson Bay.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The north part of Alberta was a prime habitat for fur-bearing animals and was targeted by the HBC and other fur trading companies.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The first European explorer of the Athabasca region was fur trader Peter Pond, who learned of the Methye Portage, a convenient route to travel from rivers in the Hudson Bay watershed to rivers north of Rupert's Land.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] He and other Canadian fur traders formed the North West Company (NWC) of Montreal in 1779, to compete with the HBC.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The NWC built posts at many points across the northern part of Alberta territory.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Peter Pond built Fort Athabasca on Lac la Biche in 1778.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Roderick Mackenzie built Fort Chipewyan on Lake Athabasca ten years later in 1788.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] His cousin, Sir Alexander Mackenzie, followed the North Saskatchewan River to its northernmost point near Edmonton, then trekked on foot to the Athabasca River, which he followed downstream to Lake Athabasca.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] It was there he discovered the mighty outflow river that bears his name – the Mackenzie River – which he followed to its outlet in the Arctic Ocean.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Returning to Lake Athabasca, he followed the Peace River upstream and crossed the Rockies, eventually reaching the Pacific Ocean, and so he became the first European to cross the North American continent north of Mexico.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The extreme southernmost portion of Alberta was part of the French (and Spanish) territory of Louisiana, which was sold to the United States in 1803.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In the Treaty of 1818, the portion of the Louisiana territory north of the Forty-Ninth Parallel was ceded to the United Kingdom.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The area was grouped with Rupert's Land to make the North-Western Territory.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Fur trade expanded in the north, but there was intense friction and competition between the rival HBC and NWC.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 1821 the British government forced them to merge to stop the hostilities.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] After amalgamation, the Hudson's Bay Company dominated the economy of Alberta until 1870, when HBC control of Rupert's Land was ended and the territory was transferred to the newly federated Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Southern Alberta, Northern Alberta, other parts of the Northland and Rupert's land became Canada's North-West Territories.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] First Nations and representatives of the Crown negotiated the Numbered Treaties, in which the Crown gained title to the land that would later become Alberta, and the Crown committed to the ongoing support of the First Nations and guaranteed their hunting and fishing rights.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The most significant treaties for Alberta are Treaty 6 (1876), Treaty 7 (1877) and Treaty 8 (1899).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The District of Alberta was created as part of the North-West Territories on 8 May 1882.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] As settlement increased, local representatives to the North-West Legislative Assembly and the House of Commons were elected, and senators appointed, to represent Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] After a long campaign for autonomy, on 1 September 1905, the District of Alberta was enlarged and given provincial status, with the election of a Liberal majority with Alexander Cameron Rutherford as the first premier.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] At first the economy was very active, then around 1912, Alberta suffered a recession.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The First World War presented special challenges to the new province as an extraordinary number of working-age men volunteered for active service, leaving relatively few workers to maintain services and production.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Over 50% of Alberta's doctors volunteered for service overseas.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 1918 Albertans experienced the 1918 flu epidemic.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta voters sought innovation, electing a Farmers government in 1921, then the world's first Social Credit government in 1935.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta's economy stayed sluggish, especially during the Depression.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] But discovery of oil at Leduc in 1946 opened a new era of prosperity and wealth for the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] On June 21, 2013, during the 2013 Alberta floods Alberta experienced heavy rainfall that triggered catastrophic flooding throughout much of the southern half of the province along the Bow, Elbow, Highwood and Oldman rivers and tributaries.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] A dozen municipalities in Southern Alberta declared local states of emergency on June 21 as water levels rose and numerous communities were placed under evacuation orders.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 2016, the Fort McMurray wildfire resulted in the largest fire evacuation of residents in Alberta's history, as more than 80,000 people were ordered to evacuate.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Like the rest of the world, Alberta was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic starting in 2020.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The last restrictions were lifted in 2022.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Statistics Canada estimated the province to have a population of 4,931,601 in Q4 of 2024.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Since 2000, Alberta's population has experienced a relatively high rate of growth, mainly because of its burgeoning economy.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Between 2003 and 2004, the province had high birthrates (on par with some larger provinces such as British Columbia), relatively high immigration, and a high rate of interprovincial migration compared to other provinces.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 2016, Alberta continued to have the youngest population among the provinces with a median age of 36.7 years, compared with the national median of 41.2 years.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Also in 2016, Alberta had the smallest proportion of seniors (12.3%) among the provinces and one of the highest population shares of children (19.2%), further contributing to Alberta's young and growing population.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] About 81% of the population lives in urban areas and only about 19% in rural areas.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Calgary–Edmonton Corridor is the most urbanized area in the province and is one of the most densely populated areas of Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Many of Alberta's cities and towns have experienced very high rates of growth in recent history.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Additionally, as per the 2016 census, 1,769,500 residents hold a postsecondary certificate, diploma or degree, 895,885 residents have obtained a secondary (high) school diploma or equivalency certificate, and 540,665 residents do not have any certificate, diploma or degree.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The question on knowledge of languages allows for multiple responses.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] As of the 2016 census, English is the most common mother tongue, with 2,991,485 native speakers.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] This is followed by Tagalog, with 99,035 speakers, German, with 80,050 speakers, French, with 72,150 native speakers, and Punjabi, with 68,695 speakers.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The 2006 census found that English, with 2,576,670 native speakers, was the most common mother tongue of Albertans, representing 79.99% of the population.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The next most common mother tongues were Chinese with 97,275 native speakers (3.02%), followed by German with 84,505 native speakers (2.62%) and French with 61,225 (1.90%).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The most common aboriginal language is Cree 17,215 (0.53%).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] According to Statistics Canada, Alberta is home to the second-highest proportion (2%) of Francophones in western Canada (after Manitoba).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Despite this, relatively few Albertans claim French as their mother tongue.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Many of Alberta's French-speaking residents live in the central and northwestern regions of the province, after migration from other areas of Canada or descending from Métis.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta has considerable ethnic diversity.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In line with the rest of Canada, many Albertans are descended from immigrants of Western European nations, notably England, Scotland, Ireland, Wales and France, but large numbers later came from other regions of Europe, notably Germany, Ukraine and Scandinavia.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] More recently, Africans, Asians and South Americans in larger numbers have also contributed to Alberta's ethnic origins.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Many Alberta families today can trace their ethnicity in many directions.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Amongst those of British heritage, the Scots have had a particularly strong influence on place-names.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Many cities and towns have names of Scottish origins, such as Calgary, Airdrie, Canmore, and Banff.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Both Edmonton and Calgary have historic Chinatowns, and Calgary has Canada's third-largest Chinese community.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Chinese presence began with workers employed in the building of the Canadian Pacific Railway in the 1880s.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] In 2021, 27.8% of the population consisted of visible minorities and 6.8% of the population was Indigenous, mostly of First Nations and Métis descent.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] A small number of Inuit live in the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] The Indigenous population has been growing at a faster rate than the population of Alberta as a whole.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Some of this increase is due to Albertans who are only now embracing their Metis lineage.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] As of the 2011 National Household Survey, the largest religious group was Roman Catholic, representing 24.3% of the population.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta had the second-highest percentage of non-religious residents among the provinces (after British Columbia) at 31.6% of the population.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Of the remainder, 7.5% of the population identified themselves as belonging to the United Church of Canada, while 3.9% were Anglican.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Lutherans made up 3.3% of the population while Baptists constituted 1.9%.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Members of LDS Church are mostly concentrated in the extreme south of the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta has a population of Hutterites, a communal Anabaptist sect similar to the Mennonites, and has a significant population of Seventh-day Adventists.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta is home to several Byzantine Rite Churches as part of the legacy of Eastern European immigration, including the Ukrainian Catholic Eparchy of Edmonton, and the Ukrainian Orthodox Church of Canada's Western Diocese which is based in Edmonton.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Muslims made up 3.2% of the population, Sikhs 1.5%, Buddhists 1.2%, and Hindus 1.0%.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Many of these are immigrants, but others have roots that go back to the first settlers of the prairies.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Canada's oldest mosque, the Al-Rashid Mosque, is in Edmonton, whereas Calgary is home to Canada's largest mosque, the Baitun Nur Mosque.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Alberta is also home to a growing Jewish population of about 15,400 people who constituted 0.3% of Alberta's population.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p01] Most of Alberta's Jews live in the metropolitan areas of Calgary (8,200) and Edmonton (5,500).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] While most Albertans work in the service sector, Alberta does possess a significant industrial base, intelligence economy and energy sector.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] This energy sector is famously focused in oil and gas extraction.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Oil and gas has been culturally influential, having shaped politics, generated "striking it rich" narratives, and created boom-and-bust cycles.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The majority of Alberta's exports are sent to the United States, and consist of 70% oil and gas, 13% food products, and 12% industrial products.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Before European contact, Indigenous peoples maintained wide trade networks across Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Then, the fur trade, dominated by the Hudson's Bay Company and the North West Company became the region's first major export economy in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Following the transfer of Rupert's Land to Canada in 1870, Alberta's economy transitioned to agriculture and ranching.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The completion of the Canadian Pacific Railway in the 1880s facilitated large-scale settlement and grain exports, particularly wheat, establishing agriculture as the province's new economic backbone.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] A major shift came in 1947 with the discovery of oil near Leduc, launching Alberta's rise as Canada's top oil producer.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] While oil brought prosperity, the 1980s, 2008 and 2014 saw economic setbacks due to price crashes.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Since then, Alberta has worked to diversify its economy, expanding into technology, renewable energy, tourism, and finance to reduce its dependence on oil.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Agriculture employed 35,900 people in 2021, representing roughly 2% of provincial employment.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Out of them, 19,500 were employed in animal production, 11,800 were employed in crop production, 2,000 were employed in mix farming and 2,600 in support activities or agriculture.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The province has over three million head of cattle, and Alberta beef has a healthy worldwide market.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Forty per cent of all Canadian beef is produced in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The province also produces the most bison meat in Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Sheep for wool and mutton are also raised.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Wheat and canola are primary farm crops, with Alberta leading the provinces in spring wheat production; other grains are also prominent.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Much of the farming is dryland farming, often with fallow seasons interspersed with cultivation.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Continuous cropping (in which there is no fallow season) is gradually becoming a more common mode of production because of increased profits and a reduction of soil erosion.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Across the province, the once common grain elevator is slowly being lost as rail lines are decreasing; farmers typically truck the grain to central points.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2016, forestry provided over 15,000 jobs and generated over $1.0 billion to employment income, $2.6 billion to the provincial GDP, and over $6.1 billion in revenue.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Uses for harvested timber include pulpwood, hardwood, engineered wood and bioproducts such as chemicals and biofuels.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Hybrid canola also requires bee pollination, and some beekeepers service this need.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The mining and quarrying sector, excluding oil and gas, employed approximately 4,300 Albertans in 2021 (around 0.2% of the population) and focused on the mining of coal and mineral resources, such as sand, gravel, salt, limestone, clay, shale and more.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Oil and gas extraction itself however is Alberta's largest and most economically dominant primary industry.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2021, the industry employed roughly 84,500 people in extraction, with another 50,500 in support activities—totaling approximately 135,000 jobs or about 5.6% of Alberta's total employment.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In terms of economic output, the sector accounted for approximately 27% of Alberta's GDP in 2022.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta also produced about 4.3 million barrels (680,000 m3) of crude oil per day in 2023, making up 84% of Canada's total oil production.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta is the largest producer of conventional crude oil, synthetic crude, natural gas and gas products in Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta is the world's second-largest exporter of natural gas and the fourth-largest producer.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Two of the largest producers of petrochemicals in North America are in central and north-central Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In both Red Deer and Edmonton, polyethylene and vinyl manufacturers produce products that are shipped all over the world.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Edmonton's oil refineries provide the raw materials for a large petrochemical industry to the east of Edmonton.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The Athabasca oil sands surrounding Fort McMurray have estimated unconventional oil reserves approximately equal to the conventional oil reserves of the rest of the world, estimated to be 1.6 trillion barrels (250 km3).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Many companies employ both conventional strip mining and non-conventional in situ methods to extract the bitumen from the oil sands.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Another factor determining the viability of oil extraction from the oil sands is the price of oil.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The oil price increases since 2003 have made it profitable to extract this oil, which in the past would give little profit or even a loss.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] By mid-2014, rising costs and stabilizing oil prices threatened the economic viability of some projects.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] An example of this was the shelving of the Joslyn North project in the Athabasca region in May 2014.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] With concerted effort and support from the provincial government, several high-tech industries have found their birth in Alberta, notably patents related to interactive liquid-crystal display systems.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] While not as important as its service sector or as influential as its oil and gas industry, Alberta's secondary sector — comprising manufacturing, construction, and utilities — is still of importance, especially to employment and economic diversification.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2021, Alberta's manufacturing sector employed approximately 122,300 individuals, accounting for 5% of the province's total employment.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The sector also contributed $23.4 billion, or 8%, to Alberta's Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Key subsectors include food manufacturing (15.8% of manufacturing employment), fabricated metal products (13.6%), machinery (9.8%), wood products (9.8%), and chemicals (8.7%).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Notably, 96% of these jobs were full-time, and 73% of the workforce fell within the core working age of 25–54.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] However, with 20% of workers aged 55 and older, the sector faces impending retirements that could lead to significant job vacancies.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta's construction industry is a major employer, with 222,200 individuals working in the sector in 2021, representing 10% of the province's workforce.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The industry contributed $23.6 billion to Alberta's GDP, equating to 8% of the total.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Employment is distributed across trade contracting (54.8%), building construction (30.8%), and heavy and civil engineering construction (14.4%).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The workforce is predominantly male (84%), with a significant portion (27%) being self-employed.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Additionally, Indigenous workers constitute 13.5% of the construction labor force, surpassing their representation in the overall provincial workforce.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The utilities sector, which encompasses electricity generation, transmission, and distribution, employed 13,354 Albertans in 2022.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Employment here grew at an average annual rate of 2.6% between 2017 and 2022, largely because of the expansion of renewable energy sources.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta's service sector employs around 80% of Albertans, in various fields like retail, healthcare, education, professional services, tourism, FIRE (finance, investment and real estate), transportation and warehousing, food services, public administration, arts and recreation, and more.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Therefore, it unsurprisingly accounts for the majority of Alberta's economic activity.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The retail and wholesale trade sector is a significant employer in Alberta, accounting for approximately 15% of total provincial employment.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2022, wholesale trade contributed $14.7 billion, and retail trade contributed $14.1 billion to Alberta's GDP, collectively making up about 8% of the province's total GDP.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Healthcare and social assistance, which includes hospitals, clinics, nursing homes and community health programs, is similarly one of the largest employers in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2020, approximately 247,100 individuals were employed in this sector, representing about 11% of the province's total employment.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] About 88,800 of these jobs are in the ambulatory health care services sub-sector, while 107,800 are employed in the hospitals sub-sector and 50,500 are employed in nursing and residential care facilities.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In terms of economic contribution, the sector added $16.7 billion to Alberta's GDP in 2020, accounting for 5.4% of the provincial total.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Employment prospects here are good, due to an aging population and ongoing labor shortages, particularly in nursing and residential care facilities.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Educational services account for 7.1% of total provincial employment in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2022, of the 168,100 people employed here, about 98,400 people (58.5%) worked in primary and secondary education, 36,400 people (21.7%) worked in university education, 17,800 (10.6%) worked in other schools and educational support, and 12,200 (7.3%) worked in post-secondary education.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2022, the sector contributed $12.4 billion, or 4%, to the provincial GDP.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The finance, insurance, real estate and leasing (or FIRE) is a big part of Alberta's economy.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2023, the finance and insurance sector alone contributed $14.88 billion to the province's GDP, with a five-year average growth rate of 2.8%.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In February 2025, activity in this sub-sector declined for the third consecutive month, reflecting a cooling in home resale activity across the country.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The professional, scientific, and technical services sector has experienced rapid growth in recent times, with employment increasing by 28,700 jobs (15.1%) between 2021 and 2022.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Since 2018, employment has grown by 47,300 jobs (27.6%), making it one of the fastest-growing sectors in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The transportation and warehousing sector employed 130,900 people in 2021, accounting for 6% of total provincial employment.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Employment in this sector increased by 10,600 jobs (8.8%) from 2020 to 2021.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2022, approximately 108,200 people were employed in Alberta's public administration sector, accounting for 4.6% of provincial employment.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Employment in this sector increased by 5,000 jobs (4.8%) from 2021 to 2022.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The arts, entertainment, and recreation sector contributed $1.61 billion to Alberta's GDP in 2023, with an 8.2% growth.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] However, over a five-year period, the sector experienced an annualized -3.7% GDP and -3.5% employment decline, despite employing 22,663 people in 2023.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] This may be due to COVID-19 pandemic-related disruptions, but lower funding from government, higher difficulty in obtaining and retaining staff, and shifts in consumer behaviour could also be contributing factors.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The accommodation and food services -which encompasses accommodations, food and beverage services, recreation and entertainment, and travel services- is a significant component of Alberta's service economy.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] 140,400 people were employed here in 2023, which accounts for 6.1% of Alberta's total employment.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Furthermore, in 2023, the sector contributed approximately $8.1 billion to Alberta's GDP, marking a 7.8% increase from the previous year.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] This growth indicates a strong recovery from the pandemic's impact, with the sector surpassing pre-pandemic levels for the first time.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] According to Alberta Economic Development, Calgary and Edmonton both host over four million visitors annually.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Banff, Jasper and the Rocky Mountains are visited by about three million people per year.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta tourism relies heavily on Southern Ontario tourists, as well as tourists from other parts of Canada, the United States, and many other countries.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] There are also natural attractions like Elk Island National Park, Wood Buffalo National Park, and the Columbia Icefield.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta's Rockies include well-known tourist destinations Banff National Park and Jasper National Park.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The two mountain parks are connected by the scenic Icefields Parkway.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Banff is located 128 km (80 mi) west of Calgary on Highway 1, and Jasper is located 366 km (227 mi) west of Edmonton on the Yellowhead Highway.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Five of Canada's fourteen UNESCO World Heritage Sites are located within the province: Canadian Rocky Mountain Parks, Waterton-Glacier International Peace Park, Wood Buffalo National Park, Dinosaur Provincial Park and Head-Smashed-In Buffalo Jump.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] A number of these areas hold ski resorts, most notably Banff Sunshine, Lake Louise, Marmot Basin, Norquay and Nakiska.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] About 1.2 million people visit the Calgary Stampede, a celebration of Canada's own Wild West and the cattle ranching industry.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] About 700,000 people enjoy Edmonton's K-Days (formerly Klondike Days and Capital EX).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Edmonton was the gateway to the only all-Canadian route to the Yukon gold fields, and the only route which did not require gold-seekers to travel the exhausting and dangerous Chilkoot Pass.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Another tourist destination that draws more than 650,000 visitors each year is the Drumheller Valley, located northeast of Calgary.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Drumheller, known as the "Dinosaur Capital of The World", offers the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Drumheller also had a rich mining history being one of Western Canada's largest coal producers during the war years.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Another attraction in east-central Alberta is Alberta Prairie Railway Excursions, a popular tourist attraction operated out of Stettler, that offers train excursions into the prairie and caters to tens of thousands of visitors every year.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The Government of Alberta is organized as a parliamentary democracy with a unicameral legislature.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Its unicameral legislature—the Legislative Assembly—consists of 87 members elected first past the post (FPTP) from single-member constituencies.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Locally municipal governments and school boards are elected and operate separately.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Their boundaries do not necessarily coincide.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] As King of Canada, Charles III is the head of state of Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] His duties concerning the Government of Alberta are carried out by Lieutenant Governor Salma Lakhani.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The King and lieutenant governor are figureheads whose actions are highly restricted by custom and constitutional convention.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The lieutenant governor handles numerous honorific duties in the name of the King.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The government is headed by the premier.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The premier is normally a member of the Legislative Assembly, and draws all the members of the Cabinet from among the members of the Legislative Assembly.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The City of Edmonton is the seat of the provincial government—the capital of Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The current premier is Danielle Smith, who was sworn in on October 11, 2022.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta's elections have tended to yield much more conservative outcomes than those of other Canadian provinces.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] From the 1980s to the 2010s, Alberta had three main political parties, the Progressive Conservatives ("Conservatives" or "Tories"), the Liberals, and the social democratic New Democrats.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The strongly conservative Social Credit Party was a power in Alberta for many decades, but fell from the political map after the Progressive Conservatives came to power in 1971.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] For 44 years the Progressive Conservatives governed Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] All types of municipalities are governed by local residents and were incorporated under various provincial acts, with the exception of improvement districts (governed by either the provincial or federal government), and Indian reserves (governed by local band governments under federal jurisdiction).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Policing in the province of Alberta upon its creation was the responsibility of the Royal Northwest Mounted Police.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 1917, due to pressures of the First World War, the Alberta Provincial Police was created.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] This organization policed the province until it was disbanded as a Great Depression-era cost-cutting measure in 1932.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] It was at that time the, now renamed, Royal Canadian Mounted Police resumed policing of the province, specifically RCMP "K" Division.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] With the advent of the Alberta Sheriffs Branch, the distribution of duties of law enforcement in Alberta has been evolving as certain aspects, such as traffic enforcement, mobile surveillance and the close protection of the Premier of Alberta have been transferred to the Sheriffs.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2006, Alberta formed the Alberta Law Enforcement Response Teams (ALERT) to combat organized crime and the serious offences that accompany it.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] ALERT is made up of members of the RCMP, Sheriffs Branch, and various major municipal police forces in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Military bases in Alberta include Canadian Forces Base (CFB) Cold Lake, CFB Edmonton, CFB Suffield and CFB Wainwright.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Air force units stationed at CFB Cold Lake have access to the Cold Lake Air Weapons Range.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] CFB Edmonton is the headquarters for the 3rd Canadian Division.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] CFB Suffield hosts British troops and is the largest training facility in Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] According to Alberta's 2009 budget, government revenue in that year came mainly from royalties on non-renewable natural resources (30.4%), personal income taxes (22.3%), corporate and other taxes (19.6%), and grants from the federal government primarily for infrastructure projects (9.8%).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2014, Alberta received $6.1 billion in bitumen royalties.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] With the drop in the price of oil in 2015 it was down to $1.4 billion.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2016, Alberta received "about $837 million in royalty payments from oil sands Royalty Projects".
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] According to the 2018–2021 fiscal plan, the two top sources of revenue in 2016 were personal income tax at $10,763 million and federal transfers of $7,976 million with total resource revenue at $3,097 million.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta is the only province in Canada without a provincial sales tax.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta residents are subject to the federal sales tax, the Goods and Services Tax of 5%.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] From 2001 to 2016, Alberta was the only Canadian province to have a flat tax of 10% of taxable income, which was introduced by Premier, Ralph Klein, as part of the Alberta Tax Advantage, which also included a zero-per cent tax on income below a "generous personal exemption".
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2016, under Premier Rachel Notley, while most Albertans continued to pay the 10% income tax rate, new tax brackets 12%, 14%, and 15% for those with higher incomes ($128,145 annually or more) were introduced.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta's personal income tax system maintained a progressive character by continuing to grant residents personal tax exemptions of $18,451, in addition to a variety of tax deductions for persons with disabilities, students, and the aged.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta's municipalities and school jurisdictions have their own governments who usually work in co-operation with the provincial government.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] By 2018, most Albertans continued to pay the 10% income tax rate.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] According to a March 2015 Statistics Canada report, the median household income in Alberta in 2014 was about $100,000, which is 23% higher than the Canadian national average.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Based on Statistic Canada reports, low-income Albertans, who earn less than $25,000 and those in the high-income bracket earning $150,000 or more, are the lowest-taxed people in Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Those in the middle income brackets representing those that earn about $25,000 to $75,000 pay more in provincial taxes than residents in British Columbia and Ontario.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In terms of income tax, Alberta is the "best province" for those with a low income because there is no provincial income tax for those who earn $18,915 or less.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Even with the 2016 progressive tax brackets up to 15%, Albertans who have the highest incomes, those with a $150,000 annual income or more—about 178,000 people in 2015, pay the least in taxes in Canada. — About 1.9 million Albertans earned between $25,000 and $150,000 in 2015.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta also privatized alcohol distribution.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] By 2010, privatization had increased outlets from 304 stores to 1,726; 1,300 jobs to 4,000 jobs; and 3,325 products to 16,495 products.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Tax revenue also increased from $400 million to $700 million.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2017/18 Alberta collected about $2.4 billion in education property taxes from municipalities.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta municipalities raise a significant portion of their income through levying property taxes.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The value of assessed property in Alberta was approximately $727 billion in 2011.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Most real property is assessed according to its market value.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The exceptions to market value assessment are farmland, railways, machinery and equipment and linear property, all of which is assessed by regulated rates.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Depending on the property type, property owners may appeal a property assessment to their municipal 'Local Assessment Review Board', 'Composite Assessment Review Board,' or the Alberta Municipal Government Board.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Calgary is famous for its Stampede, dubbed "The Greatest Outdoor Show on Earth".
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The Stampede is Canada's biggest rodeo festival and features various races and competitions, such as calf roping and bull riding.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In line with the western tradition of rodeo are the cultural artisans that reside and create unique Alberta western heritage crafts.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Summer brings many festivals to Alberta, especially in Edmonton.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The Edmonton Fringe Festival is the world's second-largest after the Edinburgh Festival.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Both Calgary and Edmonton host many annual festivals and events, including folk music festivals.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The city's "heritage days" festival sees the participation of over 70 ethnic groups.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Edmonton's Churchill Square is home to a large number of the festivals, including A Taste of Edmonton and The Works Art & Design Festival throughout the summer months.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The award comes with $60,000 funding which includes travel and materials costs.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] On January 31, 2019, Lauren Crazybull was named Alberta's first artist in residence.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta is the first province to launch an artist in residence program in Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] As with any Canadian province, the Alberta Legislature has (almost) exclusive authority to make laws respecting education.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] There are forty-two public school jurisdictions in Alberta, and seventeen operating separate school jurisdictions.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Sixteen of the operating separate school jurisdictions have a Catholic electorate, and one (St.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In addition, one Protestant separate school district, Glen Avon, survives as a ward of the St.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The City of Lloydminster straddles the Albertan/Saskatchewan border, and both the public and separate school systems in that city are counted in the above numbers: both of them operate according to Saskatchewan law.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] For many years, the provincial government has funded the greater part of the cost of providing K–12 education.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Prior to 1994, public and separate school boards in Alberta had the legislative authority to levy a local tax on property as supplementary support for local education.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 1994, the government of the province eliminated this right for public school boards, but not for separate school boards.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Since 1994, there has continued to be a tax on property in support of K–12 education; the difference is that the provincial government now sets the mill rate, the money is collected by the local municipal authority and remitted to the provincial government.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The relevant legislation requires that all the money raised by this property tax must go to support K–12 education provided by school boards.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The provincial government pools the property tax funds from across the province and distributes them, according to a formula, to public and separate school jurisdictions and Francophone authorities.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Public and separate school boards, charter schools, and private schools all follow the Program of Studies and the curriculum approved by the provincial department of education (Alberta Education).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Homeschool tutors may choose to follow the Program of Studies or develop their own Program of Studies.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Several publicly funded post-secondary institutions are governed under the province's *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Nine comprehensive community colleges offer primarily offer diploma and certificate programs, Bow Valley College, Keyano College, Lakeland College, Lethbridge College, Medicine Hat College, NorQuest College, Northern Lakes College, Olds College, and Portage College.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In addition, there are also four polytechnic institutes that provide specific career training and provides apprenticeships and diplomas, the Northern Alberta Institute of Technology, the Southern Alberta Institute of Technology, Northwestern Polytechnic, and Red Deer Polytechnic.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The Banff Centre for Arts and Creativity is a specialized arts and cultural institution that is also empowered to provide diploma programs under the *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta is also home to five independent postsecondary institutions that provide diplomas/degrees for approved programming, Ambrose University, Burman University, Concordia University of Edmonton, The King's University, and St.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Although the five institutions operate under their own legislation, they remain partly governed by the province's *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In addition to these institutions, there are also 190 private career colleges in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta provides a publicly funded, fully integrated health system, through Alberta Health Services (AHS)—a quasi-independent agency that delivers health care on behalf of the Government of Alberta's Ministry of Health.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The Alberta government provides health services for all its residents as set out by the provisions of the *Canada Health Act* of 1984.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta became Canada's second province (after Saskatchewan) to adopt a Tommy Douglas-style program in 1950, a precursor to the modern medicare system.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta's health care budget was $22.5 billion during the 2018–2019 fiscal year (approximately 45% of all government spending), making it the best-funded health-care system per-capita in Canada.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Every hour the province spends more than $2.5 million, (or $60 million per day), to maintain and improve health care in the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The Edmonton Clinic complex, completed in 2012, provides a similar research, education, and care environment as the Mayo Clinic in the United States.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] All public health care services funded by the Government of Alberta are delivered operationally by Alberta Health Services.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] AHS is the province's single health authority, established on July 1, 2008, which replaced nine regional health authorities.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] AHS also funds all ground ambulance services in the province, as well as the province-wide Shock Trauma Air Rescue Service (STARS) air ambulance service.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta is well-connected by air, with international airports in both Calgary and Edmonton.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Calgary International Airport and Edmonton International Airport are the fourth- and fifth-busiest in Canada, respectively.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Edmonton's airport acts as a hub for the Canadian north and has connections to all major Canadian airports as well as airports in the United States, Europe, Mexico, and the Caribbean .
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Calgary, Edmonton, Red Deer, Medicine Hat, and Lethbridge have substantial public transit systems.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In addition to buses, Calgary and Edmonton operate light rail transit (LRT) systems.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Edmonton LRT, which is underground in the downtown core and on the surface outside the downtown core was the first of the modern generation of light rail systems to be built in North America, while the Calgary CTrain has one of the highest numbers of daily riders of any LRT system in North America.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] There are more than 9,000 km (5,600 mi) of operating mainline railway in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The vast majority of this trackage is owned by the Canadian Pacific Kansas City (CPKC) and Canadian National Railway (CN) companies, which operate freight transport across the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Additional railfreight service in the province is provided by two shortline railways: the Battle River Railway and Forty Mile Rail.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Passenger trains include Via Rail's *Canadian* (Toronto–Vancouver) and Jasper–Prince Rupert trains, which use the CN mainline and pass through Jasper National Park and parallel the Yellowhead Highway during at least part of their routes.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The Rocky Mountaineer operates two sections: one from Vancouver to Banff over CP tracks, and a section that travels over CN tracks to Jasper.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] In 2024 Alberta's premier, Danielle Smith, announced a 15-year master plan to expand passenger rail in Alberta.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] This plan envisions rail services to Lethbridge, Medicine Hat, Banff, Grande Prairie, Fort McMurray, and most importantly an intercity rail service between Edmonton and Calgary, as well as commuter rail systems in the respective cities.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Ground-breaking was planned for 2027, according to Transportation Minister Devin Dreeshen.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta has over 473,000 km (294,000 mi) of highways and roads in its road network.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The main north–south corridor is Highway 2, which begins south of Cardston at the Carway border crossing and is part of the CANAMEX Corridor.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Beginning at the Coutts border crossing and ending at Lethbridge, Highway 4, effectively extends Interstate 15 into Alberta and is the busiest United States gateway to the province.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Highway 3 joins Lethbridge to Fort Macleod and links Highway 2 to Highway 4.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Highway 2 travels north through Fort Macleod, Calgary, Red Deer, and Edmonton.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] North of Edmonton, the highway continues to Athabasca, then northwesterly along the south shore of Lesser Slave Lake into High Prairie, north to Peace River, west to Fairview and finally south to Grande Prairie, where it ends at an interchange with Highway 43.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The section of Highway 2 between Calgary and Edmonton has been named the Queen Elizabeth II Highway to commemorate the visit of the monarch in 2005.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Highway 2 is supplemented by two more highways that run parallel to it: Highway 22, west of Highway 2, known as *Cowboy Trail*, and Highway 21, east of Highway 2.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Highway 43 travels northwest into Grande Prairie and the Peace River Country.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Travelling northeast from Edmonton, the Highway 63 connects to Fort McMurray and the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Alberta has two main east–west corridors.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The southern corridor, part of the Trans-Canada Highway system, enters the province near Medicine Hat, runs westward through Calgary, and leaves Alberta through Banff National Park.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The northern corridor, also part of the Trans-Canada network and known as the Yellowhead Highway (Highway 16), runs west from Lloydminster in eastern Alberta, through Edmonton and Jasper National Park into British Columbia.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] One of the most scenic drives is along the Icefields Parkway, which runs for 228 km (142 mi) between Jasper and Lake Louise, with mountain ranges and glaciers on either side of its entire length.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] A third corridor stretches across southern Alberta; Highway 3 runs between Crowsnest Pass and Medicine Hat through Lethbridge and forms the eastern portion of the Crowsnest Highway.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Another major corridor through central Alberta is Highway 11 (also known as the David Thompson Highway), which runs east from the Saskatchewan River Crossing in Banff National Park through Rocky Mountain House and Red Deer, connecting with Highway 12, 20 km (12 mi) west of Stettler.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] The highway connects many of the smaller towns in central Alberta with Calgary and Edmonton, as it crosses Highway 2 just west of Red Deer.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Urban stretches of Alberta's major highways and freeways are often called *trails*.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] For example, Highway 2, the main north–south highway in the province, is called Deerfoot Trail as it passes through Calgary but becomes Calgary Trail (southbound) and Gateway Boulevard (northbound) as it enters Edmonton and then turns into St.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Albert Trail as it leaves Edmonton for the City of St.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/alberta-p02] Calgary, in particular, has a tradition of calling its largest urban expressways *trails* and naming many of them after prominent First Nations individuals and tribes, such as Crowchild Trail, Deerfoot Trail, and Stoney Trail.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The **Australian Football Association of North America** (AFANA) is a non-profit organization that formed out of a campaign to save television coverage of Australian rules football in the United States and Canada in 1996.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] AFANA has an emphasis on the fan, and aims to help the game to develop and to improve its exposure in North America, including better TV coverage.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] AFANA was co-founded by three members of the 1995-1996 campaign: Richard Lipp of Kansas City, Wade Hinkle of Dallas, and Rob de Santos (then of Vienna, WV) when it was learned that the sport had no TV coverage for the 1996 season.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The campaign was ultimately successful and coverage began on the new ESPN2 ("the deuce") network in June.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The network declined to cover the Grand Final in 1996.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The AFL tried to find another network, but in the end, turned to AFANA and the Australian-American Chamber of Commerce of Southern California.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The two organizations successfully put the game on the air on satellite in the USA and Canada in just 8 days.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The following year, coverage continued on ESPN.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] Again, problems with the Grand Final occurred when ESPN delayed the broadcast 95 minutes (due to live baseball) on just 36 hours notice after repeated assurances that the game would be live.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] Despite an intense lobbying effort, ESPN did not budge.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The relationship between the Australian Football League, AFANA, and ESPN continued to be strained and after the 1997 season, the network again dropped the sport.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] With AFANA's help, the sport moved to the new Fox Sports World channel the following year.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The organization has played a part in every effort to keep TV coverage since its founding including network changes in 1998, 2007, 2009, and 2012.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] In 2004, Fox announced the channel was changing names to Fox Soccer Channel and would eventually drop all non-soccer coverage.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] AFANA successfully lobbied for the coverage to continue into the 2006 season.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The following year resulted in a major success of the lobby group with the televising of live AFL matches beginning in 2007 by Setanta Sports (USA).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] Current TV coverage is again on Fox networks including Fox Sports 2 and Fox Soccer Plus, a premium network.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] Coverage was briefly lost when Setanta Sports USA went into bankruptcy in August, 2009.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] ESPN picked up coverage on its internet channel, then ESPN360 (later ESPN3) plus about 4 matches a year and the Grand Final on ESPN2.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] ESPN did not renew the contract after 2011.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] Weekly coverage returned in 2012 to Fox Soccer Plus the successor channel to Fox Sports World.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] For the 2018 season, officials at the Australian Football League have told AFANA coverage will continue on Fox Soccer Plus and on through the 2020 season.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] A post on the AFANA website says Fox Soccer Plus will broadcast a minimum of 2 live games per week.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] The network has also committed to show all finals matches, leading up to and including the Grand Final.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] AFANA consolidates the schedules of every network in North America which carries the sport into one listing on its web site, a major convenience for fans.
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] One of AFANA's major services is the posting of announcements of the many AFL Grand Final parties held in North America (and sometimes Europe and Asia).
[src:49th-parallel-cup/australian-football-association-of-north-america] These yearly parties are typically held the day of the Grand Final and usually feature Australian food and beverages as the staple refreshments for the event.
